kernel_variant.question:
Let $n$ be a positive integer and $q$ a formal variable with $|q|<1$.

Prove the $q$-Chu-Vandermonde convolution  
\[
\boxed{\;
\displaystyle 
\sum_{r=0}^{n} q^{\,r(r-1)}
      \begin{bmatrix} n\\ r \end{bmatrix}_{\!q}
      \begin{bmatrix} n\\ r-1 \end{bmatrix}_{\!q}
      \;=\;
      \begin{bmatrix} 2n\\ n-1 \end{bmatrix}_{\!q}}
\tag{$\star$}
\]
under the convention $\bigl[\begin{smallmatrix} n\\ -1\end{smallmatrix}\bigr]_{q}=0$, where  
\[
\begin{bmatrix} m\\ k\end{bmatrix}_{\!q}
=\frac{(q;q)_m}{(q;q)_k\,(q;q)_{m-k}},\qquad 
(a;q)_m=(1-a)(1-aq)\cdots(1-aq^{\,m-1})
\]
denotes the Gaussian (or $q$-binomial) coefficient.

Furthermore, show that letting $q\to1^{-}$ in $(\star)$ yields the classical Chu-Vandermonde identity
\[
\sum_{r=0}^{n}\binom{n}{r}\binom{n}{r-1}=\binom{2n}{\,n-1}.
\]

